**Throughout the month of September 2023, the Japanese government made a series of commitments totaling JPY2 billion (US$14 million) to promote food security in seven countries.**\
\
The funds were allocated as follows:

- JPY300 million (US$2 million) to Guinea to improve food security and nutritional conditions through the :abbr[WFP];
- JPY200 million (US$1.4 million) to Palestine to improve food security through the :abbr[WFP];
- JPY150 million (US$1 million) to Cabo Verde to support rice donations and to improve food security;
- JPY250 million (US$1.7 million) to the Central African Republic to improve food security and promote development through the :abbr[WFP];
- JPY200 million (US$1.4 million) to Cameroon to improve food security and promote development through the :abbr[WFP];
- JPY280 million (US$1.9 million) to Uzbekistan for the construction of a climate-resilient agricultural system in the Aral Sea region; and
- JPY602 million (US$4.1 million) to Mauritania to improve food security and support the fishing industry.

<br>

Japan reaffirmed its commitment to addressing the ongoing food crisis exacerbated by the Russian invasion of Ukraine.

**On September 14, 2023, the :abbr[UK] government released its final statistics on :abbr[UK] :abbr[ODA] spending for 2022.**\
\
The figures showed that the :abbr[UK] spent GBP13 billion (US$15 billion), or 0.51% of its :abbr[GNI], on :abbr[ODA]. In 2022, the data showed an increase in current prices of GBP1 billion (US$2 billion) from 2021 levels.\
\
The :abbr[UK] spent GBP4 million (US$4 million), or 28.8%, on in-donor refugee costs. :abbr[BOND]{title="the UK umbrella organization representing numerous international development NGOs"} criticized the :abbr[UK] for spending such a large share of its :abbr[ODA] budget in-donor refugee costs and noted that this increase came at the expense of funding for vulnerable partner countries.\
\
Other key statistics included:  
- *:abbr[UK] bilateral and multilateral spending:* :abbr[UK] bilateral :abbr[ODA] spending increased in 2022 and stood at GBP10 million (US$12 million), or 75.3% of total :abbr[UK] :ABBR[ODA]. Much of the 33% increase in bilateral funding was allocated to in-donor refugee costs. Core multilateral funding accounted for GBP3 million (US$4 million), or 24.7% of total :abbr[UK] :ABBR[ODA]. This is the lowest share of multilateral :abbr[ODA] in recent years. The :abbr[UK] met its commitment made in its 2022 International Development Strategy to deliver 75% of its :abbr[ODA] bilaterally;
- *Distribution of :abbr[ODA] across government departments:* The :ABBR[FCDO] was accountable for just 59.7% of :abbr[ODA] in 2022, down from 71.6%, and was driven primarily by in-donor refugee costs. The :ABBR[FCDO] spent GBP7.6 million (US$9.1 million) on :abbr[ODA] in 2022, compared with GBP8.2 million (US$9.8 million) in 2021. In contrast, the :abbr[UK] Home Office, spent GBP2 million (US$3 million) of :abbr[ODA] in 2022, a 130.2% increase compared to 2021;
- *Regional spending:* Africa remained the largest recipient of :abbr[UK] region-specific bilateral :abbr[ODA] in 2022, accounting for 42.2% of :abbr[ODA]. However, bilateral :abbr[ODA] to Africa decreased by 28.2%, from GBP1.7 million (US$2 million) in 2021 to GBP1.2 million (US$1.5 million) in 2022. This is the lowest level of :abbr[ODA] to Africa in recent years;
- *Top three recipients of :abbr[UK] bilateral :abbr[ODA]:* The top three recipients of :abbr[UK] bilateral country-specific :abbr[ODA] were Afghanistan (GBP352 million (US$421 million)), Ukraine (GBP342 million (US$409 million)) and Nigeria (GBP110 million (US$131 million)); 
- *Top five bilateral :abbr[ODA] sectors:* The largest amount of bilateral :abbr[ODA] was focused on the sectors ‘Refugees in Donor Countries’ (GBP4 million (US$4 million)), ‘Humanitarian (GBP1 million (US$1 million)) and ‘Health’ (GBP976 million (US$1.2 billion));
- *Top five recipient of :abbr[UK] multilateral :abbr[ODA]:* The :abbr[EU] remained the largest recipient from the :abbr[UK], though the volume of funding decreased. The second-largest recipient of :abbr[UK] multilateral :abbr[ODA] was the Global Fund, followed by the World Bank’s :abbr[IDA], the :abbr[ADF] and the :abbr[GCF]; and
- *Pandemic funding*: In 2022, approximately GBP270 million (US$323 million) of :abbr[UK] bilateral :abbr[ODA] was spent on activities which specifically addressed the :abbr[COVID-19] pandemic. :ABBR[FCDO] accounted for 96% of pandemic :ABBR[ODA]. This included the :abbr[UK]’s donation of excess vaccine doses, both directly and through :abbr[COVAX], estimated at GBP228 million (US$273 million).

<br>

The report noted that these figures have not been subject to international verification by the :abbr[OECD].

**On September 2, 2023, the :ABBR[UK] government published a report highlighting the :ABBR[UK]’s progress in implementation of the :ABBR[UK]’s Strategy for International Development, originally published in May 2022.**\
\
The progress report highlighted the :abbr[UK]'s efforts in:
- Helping to support sustainable growth by: allocating GBP2.3 billion (US$2.8 billion) of new guarantees with key :abbr[MDB]s to support sustainability in partner countries, signing Just Energy Transition Partnerships with South Africa, Indonesia, Vietnam, and Senegal to support clean energy, and providing GBP588 million (US$704 million) in private and public finance for clean energy innovation through the Ayrton Fund;
- Supporting vulnerable communities facing humanitarian crises by: providing a provisional total of GBP1.06 billion (US$1.3 billion) in humanitarian aid in 2022 to countries including Syria, Sudan, Turkey, Afghanistan, and Ukraine;
- Strengthening global health by: hosting the Global Pandemic Preparedness Summit in 2022 alongside :abbr[CEPI] to raise more than GBP1.1 billion (US$1.3 billion) for :abbr[PPR], helping secure multilateral agreement for a legally binding global :abbr[PPR] instrument, pledging GBP25 million (US$30 million) to a new pandemic preparedness fund, and funding :ABBR[UK] research on a new insecticide for malaria bed nets, which is currently protecting 63 million people;
- Promoting open science for global resilience by: investing GBP300 million (US$359 million) in :abbr[R&D] to strengthen local resilience in partner countries, which includes new research with the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation to increase agricultural yields by up to 20% for certain crops while protecting biodiversity. Additionally, providing funding for the Global Innovation Fund;
- Supporting girls’ education and women’s rights by: helping build a Global Coalition for Foundational Learning alongside :abbr[USAID], the World Bank, :abbr[UNESCO], :abbr[UNICEF], and the Gates Foundation that calls on governments around the world to prioritize :abbr[FLN] for marginalized children and girls. Additionally, signing a flagship GBP38 million (US$45.5 million) program in March 2023 designed to strengthen grassroots women's rights organizations and hosting the ‘Preventing Sexual Violence in Conflict Initiative’ International Conference in 2022, which led to 40 countries committing to tackle conflict-related sexual violence.
- Supporting reform of the international financial system by: allocating GBP4 billion (US$5 billion) in :abbr[SDR] through the :abbr[IMF] to deliver affordable long-term financing in low and lower-middle income countries, and working to mainstream :abbr[CRDCs]{title="Climate Resilient Debt Clauses"} in loan agreements to vulnerable countries; and
- Strengthening :ABBR[UK] :abbr[ODA] by: creating a new position for Minister for Development and Africa, creating a Ministerial :abbr[ODA] Board  to improve :abbr[ODA] spending oversight, and the establishment of a Second Permanent Secretary at the :abbr[FCDO] to oversee development priorities.

**On September 1, 2023, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs published Norway's guiding priorities for the 78<sup>th</sup>  :abbr[UN] General Assembly.**\
\
The key priorities outlined were to:
- Promote binding multilateral cooperation to increase capacity to deal with challenges such as the climate crisis, future pandemics, and the war in Ukraine;
- Promote international law and the international legal order and participate actively in forums where international law is being developed;
- Strengthen human rights, protect and promote human rights, democracy, and the rule of law, as well as integrate a rights-based approach into the :abbr[UN]'s work;
- Strengthen the :abbr[UN]’s capacity to prevent and resolve conflicts to ensure that :abbr[UN] efforts follow a nexus approach in the areas of mediation, stabilization, peace building, humanitarian response, and development;
- Continue to push for nuclear disarmament and bolster cooperative capacity to engage with nuclear-equipped states;
- Strengthen the :abbr[UN]’s capacity to prevent and respond to humanitarian crises and promote international cooperation on refugees and migrants and promote the principles of humanity, impartiality, neutrality, and independence; and
- Promote the implementation of the 2030 Agenda,  particularly concerning food security, climate and environmental issues, energy, gender equality, health, the oceans, and on reducing inequalities.

 <br>

The Norwegian delegation will include representatives of Norwegian :abbr[CSO]s. Norway has expressed interest in a 'nexus approach' to achieve the :abbr[SDG]s and underlined the importance of improving the coordination between humanitarian action, peace building, and long-term development efforts.
